==α-rhombohedral boron== α-rhombohedral boron has a unit cell of twelve boron atoms. The structure consists of {{chem|B|12}} icosahedra in which each boron atom has five nearest neighbors within the icosahedron. If the bonding were the conventional [[covalent]] type then each boron would have donated five electrons. However, boron has only three valence electrons, and it is thought that the bonding in the {{chem|B|12}} icosahedra is achieved by the so-called 3-center electron-deficient bonds where the electron charge is accumulated at the center of a triangle formed by three adjacent atoms.{{sfn|Nelmes|Loveday|Allan|Besson|1993}}
The isolated {{chem|B|12}} icosahedra are not stable; thus boron is not a molecular solid, but the icosahedra in it are connected by strong covalent bonds.
==α-tetragonal boron== Pure α-tetragonal can only be synthesized as thin layers deposited on an underlying substrate of isotropic boron carbide (B<sub>50</sub>C<sub>2</sub>) or nitride (B<sub>50</sub>N<sub>2</sub>).{{sfn|Wiberg|2001|p=930}} Most examples of α-tetragonal boron<ref>{{cite journal|title = The Structure of Tetragonal Boron| doi =10.1021/ja01550a019|year =1958 |journal =Journal of the American Chemical Society|volume =80|pages =4507|issue = 17| last1 =Hoard| first1 =J. L.| last2 =Hughes| first2 =R. E.| last3 =Sands| first3 =D. E.}}</ref> are in fact [[Boron carbides|boron-rich carbide]] or nitrides.{{sfn|Hoard|Sullenger|Kennard|1970}}{{sfn|Amberger|1981|p=61}}
==β-rhombohedral boron== β-rhombohedral boron has a unit cell containing 105–108 atoms. Most atoms form B<sub>12</sub> discrete icosahedra; a few form partially interpenetrating icosahedra, and there are two deltahedral B<sub>10</sub> units, and a single central B atom.{{sfn|Wiberg|2001|p=931}} For a long time, it was unclear whether the α or β phase is most stable at ambient conditions; however, gradually a consensus was reached that the β phase is the most thermodynamically stable allotrope.{{sfn|Oganov|Chen|Ma|Glass|2009}}<ref>{{cite journal| title = A Unifying Electron-Counting Rule for Macropolyhedral Boranes, Metallaboranes, and Metallocenes|author = Jemmis, E.D. |author2=Balakrishnarajan, M.M. |author3=Pancharatna, P.D.|journal = J. Am. Chem. Soc.|volume = 123|year = 2001|pages= 4313–4323| doi = 10.1021/ja003233z| pmid = 11457198| issue = 18}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal| title = Electronic structure and bonding of β-rhombohedral boron using cluster fragment approach|author = Prasad, D.L.V.K. |author2=Balakrishnarajan, M.M. |author3=Jemmis, E.D.|journal = Phys. Rev. B|volume = 72|issue = 19 |year = 2005|pages= 195102| doi = 10.1103/PhysRevB.72.195102 |bibcode=2005PhRvB..72s5102P}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal| title = Thermodynamic stability of boron: The role of defects and zero point motion|author1=van Setten M.J. |author2=Uijttewaal M.A. |author3=de Wijs G.A. |author4=de Groot R.A. |journal = J. Am. Chem. Soc.|volume = 129|year = 2007|pages= 2458–2465| doi = 10.1021/ja0631246| pmid = 17295480| issue = 9}}</ref><ref name=widom>{{cite journal| title = Symmetry-broken crystal structure of elemental boron at low temperature|author1=Widom M. |author2=Mihalkovic M. |journal = Phys. Rev. B|volume = 77|year = 2008|pages= 064113| doi = 10.1103/PhysRevB.77.064113| issue = 6|bibcode = 2008PhRvB..77f4113W |arxiv = 0712.0530 }}</ref>
==β-tetragonal boron== The β phase was produced in 1960 by hydrogen reduction of BBr<sub>3</sub> on hot [[tungsten]], [[rhenium]] or [[tantalum]] filaments at temperatures 1270–1550&nbsp;°C (i.e. [[chemical vapor deposition]]).{{sfn|Talley|La Placa|Post|1960}} Further studies have reproduced the synthesis and confirmed the absence of impurities in this phase.{{sfn|Sullenger|Phipps|Seabaugh|Hudgens|1969}}<ref>{{cite journal| title = Bildung der gitter des reinen bors| authors = Amberger, E. and Ploog, K. | journal = J. Less-Common Metals|volume = 23| page =21| year =1971| doi=10.1016/0022-5088(71)90004-X}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal| title = Kohlenstoff-induzierte gitter beim bor: I-tetragonales (B<sub>12</sub>)<sub>4</sub>B<sub>2</sub>C und (B<sub>12</sub>)<sub>4</sub>B<sub>2</sub>C<sub>2</sub>| authors = Ploog, K. and Amberger, E.|journal = J. Less-Common Metals|volume = 23| page =33| year =1971| doi=10.1016/0022-5088(71)90005-1}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal| title = Crystal structure of tetragonal boron related to α-AlB<sub>12</sub>| journal = Journal of Solid State Chemistry| volume =28| year = 1979|page = 289| doi = 10.1016/0022-4596(79)90080-X|bibcode = 1979JSSCh..28..289V| issue = 3 | last1 = Vlasse| first1 = M.| last2 = Naslain| first2 = R.| last3 = Kasper| first3 = J. S.| last4 = Ploog| first4 = K.}}</ref>
==γ-boron== [[Image:GborXRD.JPG|right|thumb|γ-boron: Comparison of X-ray diffraction data of Wentorf{{sfn|Wentorf|1965}} (bottom) with the modern data{{sfn|Oganov|Chen|Ma|Glass|2009}}]]
The γ-phase can be described as a NaCl-type arrangement of two types of clusters, B<sub>12</sub> icosahedra and B<sub>2</sub> pairs. It can be produced by compressing other boron phases to 12–20 GPa and heating to 1500–1800&nbsp;°C, and remains stable at ambient conditions.{{sfn|Oganov|Chen|Ma|Glass|2009}}{{sfn|Zarechnaya|Dubrovinsky|Dubrovinskaia|Filinchuk|2009}} There is evidence of significant charge transfer from B<sub>2</sub> pairs to the B<sub>12</sub> icosahedra in this structure;{{sfn|Oganov|Chen|Ma|Glass|2009}} in particular, lattice dynamics suggests the presence of significant long-range electrostatic interactions.
This phase was reported by Wentorf in 1965,{{sfn|Wentorf|1965}}<ref>{{cite journal |first1=E. Y.|last1= Zarechnaya|first2= L.|last2= Dubrovinsky|first3= N.|last3= Dubrovinskaia|first4= N.|last4= Miyajima|first5= Y.|last5= Filinchuk|first6= D.|last6= Chernyshov|first7= V.|last7= Dmitriev|title=Synthesis of an orthorhombic high pressure boron phase|journal=Science and Technology of Advanced Materials|volume=9|year=2008|doi=10.1088/1468-6996/9/4/044209|pages=044209‒12 |issue=4|bibcode = 2008STAdM...9d4209Z|pmc=5099640|pmid=27878026}}</ref> however neither structure nor chemical composition were established. The structure was solved using ''[[Ab initio quantum chemistry methods|ab initio]]'' [[crystal structure prediction]] calculations{{sfn|Oganov|Chen|Ma|Glass|2009}} and confirmed using [[X-ray crystallography|single crystal X-ray diffraction]].{{sfn|Zarechnaya|Dubrovinsky|Dubrovinskaia|Filinchuk|2009}}
==Cubic boron== Sullenger ''et al.'' (1969){{sfn|Sullenger|Phipps|Seabaugh|Hudgens|1969}} and McConville ''et al.'' (1976)<ref>{{cite journal | first1=G. T.|last1=McConville|first2= D. B.|last2= Sullenger|first3= R. E.|last3= Zielinski|first4= D. U.|last4= Gubser|first5= D. E.|last5= Sands |first6= J. S.|last6= Cantrell |year=1976|title=Some physical properties of cubic boron|journal=Physics Letters A |volume=58| pages= 257‒259|doi = 10.1016/0375-9601(76)90091-8 | issue=4 |bibcode = 1976PhLA...58..257M }}</ref> reported a cubic allotrope of boron, obtained in argon plasma experiments, with a unit cell of 1705±3 atoms and a density of 2.367 g/cm<sup>3</sup>. While this allotrope is occasionally mentioned in the literature,{{sfn|Amberger|1981|pp=21, 27, 74}} no subsequent work appears to have been published either confirming or discrediting its existence. Donohue (1982) commented{{sfn|Donohue|1982|p=80}} that the number of atoms in the unit cell did not appear to be icosahedrally related (the icosahedron being a motif common to boron structures).
==High-pressure superconducting phase== Compressing boron above 160 GPa produces a boron phase with an as yet unknown structure. Contrary to other phases, which are [[semiconductor]]s, this phase is a [[metal]] and becomes a [[superconductor]] with a critical temperature increasing from 4 K at 160 GPa to 11 K at 250 GPa.<ref>{{cite journal| author = [[Mikhail Eremets|Eremets, M. I.]] |title = Superconductivity in Boron| doi=10.1126/science.1062286 |journal = Science |volume = 293 |year = 2001 | pmid = 11452118| issue = 5528|bibcode = 2001Sci...293..272E| pages = 272–4 |display-authors=etal}}</ref> This structural transformation occurs at pressures at which theory predicts the icosahedra will dissociate.<ref>{{cite journal| title = High-pressure metallic phases of boron| journal = Phys. Rev. B |volume = 42| page = 9033| year = 1990| doi = 10.1103/PhysRevB.42.9033|bibcode = 1990PhRvB..42.9033M| issue = 14 | last1 = Mailhiot | first1 = C. | last2 = Grant | first2 = J. B. | last3 = McMahan | first3 = A. K. }}</ref> Speculation as to the structure of this phase has included face-centred cubic (analogous to Al); α-Ga, and body-centred tetragonal (analogous to In).<ref>{{cite encyclopedia | last1 = Polian | first1 = A. | last2 = Ovsyannikov | first2 = S. V. |last3 = Gauthier | first3 = M. |last4 = Munsch | first4 = M. |last5 = Chervin | first5 = J-C |last6 = Lemarchand | first6 = G. |editor1-first = E | editor1-last = Boldyreva| editor2-first = P. | editor2-last = Dera | encyclopedia =High-pressure crystallography: From fundamental phenomena to technological applications: Proceedings of the NATO Advanced Study Institute on High-Pressure Crystallography: Advanced Armor Materials and Protection from Explosives, Erice, Italy, 4‒14 June 2009 | title = Boron and boron-rich solids at high pressures| year = 2010 | publisher = Springer Science+Business Media|location=Dordrecht| isbn = 978-90-481-9257-1| pages =241‒250 (242)}}</ref> It has also been suggested that the nonmetal-metal transition is simply the result of a [[band gap]] closure, as occurs with iodine, rather than a structural transition.<ref>{{cite journal | first1=J.|last1=Zhao|first2=J. P.|last2=Lu|title=Pressure-induced metallization in solid boron|journal=Physical Review B|volume=66| pages= 092101 to 092105|issue=9|doi=10.1103/PhysRevB.66.092101|arxiv = cond-mat/0109550 |bibcode = 2002PhRvB..66i2101Z |year=2002}}</ref>
== Borophene == There exist several two-dimensional forms of boron (together called [[borophene]]s), and even more are predicted theoretically.<ref>{{Cite journal|title = Synthesis of borophenes: Anisotropic, two-dimensional boron polymorphs|journal = Science|year = 2015|pages = 1513–1516|volume = 350|issue = 6267|doi = 10.1126/science.aad1080|language = en|first = A. J.|last = Mannix|first2 = X.-F.|last2 = Zhou|first3 = B.|last3 = Kiraly|first4 = J. D.|last4 = Wood|first5 = D.|last5 = Alducin|first6 = B. D.|last6 = Myers|first7 = X.|last7 = Liu|first8 = B. L.|last8 = Fisher|first9 = U.|last9 = Santiago|bibcode = 2015Sci...350.1513M|pmc = 4922135}}</ref>
==Borospherene== The discovery of the quasispherical allotropic molecule [[borospherene]] (B<sub>40</sub>) was announced in July 2014.<ref name=nature>{{Cite journal | doi = 10.1038/nchem.1999 | issn = 1755-4349 | volume = advance online publication | pages = 727 | last = Zhai | first = Hua-Jin | first2 = Ya-Fan |last2=Zhao |first3=Wei-Li |last3=Li |first4=Qiang |last4=Chen |first5=Hui |last5=Bai |first6=Han-Shi |last6=Hu |first7=Zachary A. |last7=Piazza |first8=Wen-Juan |last8=Tian |first9=Hai-Gang |last9=Lu |first10=Yan-Bo |last10=Wu |first11=Yue-Wen |last11=Mu |first12=Guang-Feng |last12=Wei |first13=Zhi-Pan |last13=Liu |first14=Jun |last14=Li |first15=Si-Dian |last15=Li |first16=Lai-Sheng |last16=Wang | title = Observation of an all-boron fullerene | journal = Nature Chemistry | accessdate = 2014-08-13 | date = 2014-07-13 | url = http://www.nature.com/nchem/journal/vaop/ncurrent/full/nchem.1999.html |bibcode = 2014NatCh...6..727Z }}</ref>
==Amorphous boron== Amorphous boron contains B<sub>12</sub> [[icosahedron|regular icosahedra]] that are randomly bonded to each other without long range order.<ref>{{cite journal| title = A neutron diffraction study of amorphous boron using a pulsed source| first1 = R. G. |last1=Delaplane|first2=U.|last2= Dahlborg|first3=W. S.|last3=Howells|first4=T.|last4=Lundström|journal = Journal of Non-Crystalline Solids|volume = 106| issue=1–3|year =1988| pages = 66–69| doi = 10.1016/0022-3093(88)90229-3|bibcode = 1988JNCS..106...66D |ref = harv }}</ref> Pure amorphous boron can be produced by thermal decomposition of [[diborane]] at temperatures below 1000&nbsp;°C. Annealing at 1000&nbsp;°C converts amorphous boron to β-rhombohedral boron.<ref>{{cite journal| title = Crystallization of Massive Amorphous Boron| author = Gillespie, J. S. Jr.| journal = J. Am. Chem. Soc.| year = 1966| volume = 88|page =2423| doi = 10.1021/ja00963a011| issue = 11}}</ref> Amorphous boron nanowires (30–60&nbsp;nm thick){{sfn|Wang |Duan|2003}} or fibers<ref>{{cite journal| title = Microfabrication of three-dimensional boron structures by laser chemical processing| journal = J. Appl. Phys.|volume = 72| page = 5956|year =1992| doi = 10.1063/1.351904|author = Johansson, S. |bibcode = 1992JAP....72.5956J| issue = 12 |display-authors=etal}}</ref> can be produced by [[magnetron sputtering]] and [[laser]]-assisted [[chemical vapor deposition]], respectively; and they also convert to β-rhombohedral boron nanowires upon annealing at 1000&nbsp;°C.{{sfn|Wang |Duan|2003}}
