The '''Forrest H. Dutlinger Natural Area''' is a [[protected area]] in [[Clinton County, Pennsylvania|Clinton County]], [[Pennsylvania]], United States that includes a {{convert|158|acre|ha|adj=on}} [[old-growth forest]] of [[eastern hemlock]], [[American beech]], [[Prunus serotina|black cherry]], [[sugar maple]], and [[northern red oak]]. There are also [[eastern white pine]]s, but a few were selectively logged around 1900.  The largest tree is an eastern hemlock, {{convert|43|in|cm}} [[diameter at breast height]] and {{convert|112|ft|m}} tall.  

The old-growth forest once lay on the boundary of two lumber companies, the Goodyear and Lackawanna, but was apparently spared because of a dispute over a surveying error.

Forrest Dutlinger was a forester for the state of Pennsylvania from 1909 to 1959, beginning his career at a time of massive clear cutting of forests without any reforestation by the timber companies. Major fires were widespread and common due to most machinery being steam driven; the fires used to boil the water would ignite the surrounding area. Dutlinger also watched helplessly as the Asian [[chestnut blight]] killed all the American Chestnut trees in a matter of years. The chestnut was the most common hardwood tree in the forest at the time, and its magnificent lumber and nuts as a food source for wildlife have never been replaced.{{citation needed|date=June 2018}}

