The '''Cape Verde''' or '''Cape Verdes basslet''' (''Liopropoma emanueli'') is a species of [[grouper|basslet]] [[endemism|endemic]] to the [[Atlantic]] waters around [[Cape Verde]], western [[Africa]] where it is found at depths of about {{convert|20|m|ft}} and in rocky areas. Its length is not well understood.<ref>{{FishBase species |genus= Liopropoma|species= emanueli| month = June | year = 2017}}</ref>
The type of grouper, the basslet was first founded in the Danger diving site southwest of [[Tarrafal, Cape Verde|Tarrafal]] in the [[Santiago, Cape Verde|island of Santiago]] at 15°15'51.22" N and23°45'35.41" W, below overhanging large boulder, 20 m in depth.<ref name="Wirtz & Schliewen">Wirtz, P. & Schliewen, U. K.; 2012: A new species of ''Liopropoma'' Gill, 1862 from the Cape Verde Islands, Eastern Atlantic (Teleostei, Perciformes, Serranidae). ''Spixiana'', 35 (1): 149–154.</ref> It was named and described by [[Peter Wirtz]] and [[Ulrich K. Schliewen]] in 2012.<ref name="Wirtz & Schliewen"/> They are founded in the north of Santiago and likely the southern part.
The species is named in honour of Emanuel d’Oliveira, whose knowledge of the marine fauna of Santiago Island has been a great help to the first author during many dives.<ref name="Wirtz & Schliewen"/>
