The '''Mingbulak oil spill''' also known as the '''Fergana Valley oil spill''' was the worst terrestrial [[oil spill]] in the history of [[Asia]]. The oil spill was caused by a [[Blowout (well drilling)|blowout]] on March 2, 1992 at the Mingbulak oil field in the [[Fergana Valley]], [[Uzbekistan]] at [[Oil well|well]] #5. The Crude oil released from the well burned for two months.<ref>{{Cite book|title = The Handbook of Environmental Chemistry 27|last = Barcelo|first = Damia|publisher = Springer|year = 2014|isbn = 978-3-642-38475-2|location = Verlag Berlin Heidelberg|pages = 4}}</ref> The blowout resulted in the release of {{convert|35000|oilbbl|m3}} to {{convert|150000|oilbbl|m3}} per day. In total, {{convert|2000000|oilbbl|m3}} were collected behind emergency [[Dyke (construction)|dykes]]. The oil stopped flowing by itself. A total of 285,000 tons of oil were released, and it was the fifth largest oil spill in history.<ref>{{Cite book|title = The Basics of Oil Spill Cleanup|last = Fingas|first = Merv|publisher = CRC Press|year = 2013|isbn = 978-1-4398-6246-9|location = Boca Raton FL|pages = 10}}</ref> The spill is considered the largest inland spill in history.<ref>{{Cite book|title = Applied Environmental Biotechnology: Present Scenario and Future Trends|last = Kaushik|first = Garima|publisher = Springer|year = 2015|isbn = 978-81-322-2123-4|location = New Delhi|pages = 132}}</ref>
